04571nam a22007215i 9780585441702DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222000stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97805854417027 a10.1515/97805854417022doi  a(DE-B1597)615865  a(OCoLC)1312726684  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a306.76/62/09732211 aSantaMaria, Ben, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCruising Culture :bPromiscuity, Desire and American Gay Literature /cBen SantaMaria. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©2000  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTendencies: Identities, Texts, Cultures : TITC00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tSeries Editor's Introduction -- tIntroduction Passing Pleasures: Gay Men and Promiscuity -- t1. 'Crushed Intimacy': John Rechy and the Masculinisation of Gay Male Promiscuity -- t2. Loving the 'Alien': Larry Kramer and the Politics of Gay Male Promiscuity -- t3. 'A Landscape for Drifting': Promiscuity, Fantasy and Travel in the Memoirs of David Wojnarowicz -- tGlancing Back -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPromiscuous sexuality remains a central source of cultural fear and fascination, as seen in the resurgence of heated debates within American gay culture on its place in the era of AIDS. Cruising Culture provides the first extensive critical examination of competing understandings and experiences of promiscuity, both in post-war American gay culture and in American culture more broadly.In this original and provocative book, Ben Gove unpicks the root assumptions and contradictions which contribute to dominant punitive notions of promiscuous sex and desire. He challenges normative dichotomies between 'good' monogamous sexualities and 'bad' promiscuous sexualities by illustrating the inherent promiscuousness of all sexual desire, regardless of consciously expressed attitudes to sexual practice. The reader is guided through the maze of conflicting attitudes towards promiscuity in American gay culture with innovative readings of texts by influential, but hitherto critically neglected, authors such as Andrew Holleran, Larry Kramer, John Rechy, Edmund White and David Wojnarowicz. The book also draws on numerous critical and historical perspectives to represent an intricate picture of promiscuous sexual life in contemporary America.Cruising Culture will be essential reading for gay/elesbian/queer studies, gender studies and American studies, and for anyone else seeking a thorough discussion of the complex debates surrounding promiscuity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aGay menxSexual behaviorxUnited States. 0aGay menxSexual behaviorzUnited States. 0aGays in literature. 0aPromiscuityxUnited StatesxUSAxUnited States. 0aPromiscuityzUnited States. 4aAmerican Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z97831107804680 cprintz978074861361840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978058544170240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780585441702423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780585441702/original  a978-3-11-078046-8  Edinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK